  "prompt": "When is 70% isopropyl rubbing alcohol better than 91%?",
  "response": "70% isopropyl alcohol (IPA) is generally considered more effective than 91% IPA for disinfecting purposes, particularly for killing bacteria and viruses. Here are the reasons why 70% IPA is often preferred over 91% IPA in many applications:\n\n1. **Better Penetration**:  \n   - 70% IPA contains more water, which helps it penetrate cell walls more effectively.  \n   - The water slows down the evaporation rate, allowing the alcohol more time to disrupt the cell membranes of microorganisms.\n\n2. **Optimal Concentration for Disinfection**:  \n   - 70% IPA is the ideal concentration for denaturing proteins in microorganisms, which is key to killing them.  \n   - Higher concentrations (like 91%) evaporate too quickly and may not stay in contact with the microorganisms long enough to be effective.\n\n3. **Cost-Effectiveness**:  \n   - 70% IPA is less expensive to produce and is sufficient for most disinfection needs, making it a practical choice.\n\n4. **Safety**:  \n   - 70% IPA is less volatile and flammable compared to 91% IPA, making it safer to use in many settings.\n\n### When is 91% IPA Better?  \n91% IPA is useful in situations where rapid evaporation is desired and water residue is problematic, such as:  \n- Cleaning electronics or sensitive equipment.  \n- Removing adhesive residues or grease.  \n\nIn summary, 70% IPA is better for disinfection and general sanitization, while 91% IPA is more specialized for specific cleaning tasks where water content could be an issue.",
